dismissalComment.html: big appeal for caught behind, they're going up with the noise, but could it be bat hitting ground? Australia go for review. It's a very full, very wide delivery, that Brownlie looks to slice off the open face. Chris Brown, the on-field umpire, said no. But snicko points out a spike as the ball passes the bat. Umpire Dharmasena asks the decision to be reversed and so Handscomb has a second catch, this one diving forward to pick up a ball that is dying on his way through to him

of all the balls to fall to. This is full. This is miles down leg. This has boundary written all over it, and Latham tries to oblige, flicking the ball in the air, looking for the fine leg boundary. commentPostTextItems.html: Celebration all around. Williamson is being presented the trophy by Sir Richard Hadlee. They're all smiles, this has been a series win well-deserved. Hope you enjoyed our coverage, but New Zealand's home season is far from over. They host South Africa now for one T20I at Eden Park (17 February) followed by an ODI series and three Tests. Do join us then. There's plenty of cricket elsewhere to keep you connected. Hope to see you soon. Cheers and thanks for joining us.

For those who missed the action, here's our collection of the 'Plays of the day.' If pictures are what you fancy, we've got some of the best pictures from the game. And last but not least, here's Brydon Coverdale with the match bulletin

"Both games were fairly similar. The wickets were similar, on these grounds you're never out of the game. Australia showed why they're a top side, at times we felt we had them, but they kept coming hard. Credit to our guys for sucking up the pressure," Kane Williamson says. "Ross Taylor's was a brilliant hundred. The way he rotated the strike was superb. He hardly faced any dot balls, was able to build partnerships with the top order and the lower order.

Aaron Finch says Australia always felt it was a total they could chase down. "Fifties don't win you games. We saw Ross Taylor get a hundred. That is what we needed to do. Trent Boult bowled beautifully, credit to the groundsman. The surface was fantastic. The way we've dragged games back is something we'll take back."

Trent Boult is the Player of the Match. "It felt pretty good, one hell of a game," he says. "We were a few runs short, but we still finished nicely with Mitch. The conditions are familiar, I've played some cricket here. Couple of deliveries jumped and gripped, it was a two-paced wicket. This win is satisfying. We had a couple of tough lessons on tour in Australia couple of months ago."

6.50pm I wouldn't want to be picking the Man of the Match award, folks. Ross Taylor came up with a special century and two outstanding slip catches. Trent Boult ran in fast, swung the ball late and kept chipping away at the wickets every time his captain threw him the ball. Who is your pick? For the record, New Zealand have moved above India to No. 3 in the ODI rankings as a result of this win.
Most consecutive bilateral ODI series wins at home: 17 SA 2002 to 2009, 9 WI 1981 to 1990, 8 NZ 2015 to 2017 , 7 Eng, 2010 to 2012, SA 2013 to 2017*
Richard : "Boult deserves MOM no question. Today's game is heavily weighted in favour of the batsman and bowlers are ignored too often. Great performance from Taylor, but today's Boult's day."

dismissalText.commentary: Josh Hazlewood b Boult 4 (5b 1x4 0x6 5m) SR: 80

dismissalComment.html: you beauty, Boult! Six wickets and New Zealand have regained the Chappell-Hadlee Trophy. Subtle change in pace with that length ball, Hazlewood look to force that through the off side, plays outside the line and can only get a thick inside edge back onto the stumps. New Zealand win the series 2-0. These are Boult's best figures in ODIs, his second five-wicket haul in his career, and both have come against Australia. The last time he did it - at the 2015 World Cup at Eden Park - was equally special.

dismissalText.commentary: Shaun Marsh run out (Santner/Latham) 22 (22b 4x4 0x6 29m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: real bonus for New Zealand. Marsh was really slow on the turn. This was full on the pads, he flicked this towards deep square, where Mitchell Santner got to the ball quickly and fired a throw on the halfvolley to Latham, who did the rest. Have to say that was an excellent take from the keeper, and Marsh is caught comfortably short of the crease. Why would you want to self-destruct like that? He was just starting to play some gorgeous shots

dismissalText.commentary: Peter Handscomb b Boult 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 2m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: chopped on! New Zealand are back and indecision in footwork has cost Handscomb. Simply wafts at an away-going length ball, nothing shot really. No feet movement whatsoever. The ball crashes into the stumps off the inside edge

dismissalText.commentary: Aaron Finch c Boult b Williamson 56 (64b 5x4 2x6 86m) SR: 87.5

dismissalComment.html: got lucky with the previous delivery, this time he muscles it straight to the lone man at deep midwicket. Looked to go over long-on perhaps, ended up dragging it a bit, and towards the longer boundary there, he stood no chance. New Zealand back into this

dismissalText.commentary: Glenn Maxwell c Latham b Santner 0 (3b 0x4 0x6 3m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: this one drifts back in, pitches outside off and spins away, Maxwell shapes to cut, gets the thinnest of edges through to Latham who rides the bounce and takes an excellent catch. Very thin spike, there wasn't much on hotspot either. Maxwell shakes his head as he walks off

dismissalText.commentary: Travis Head c Brownlie b Boult 53 (72b 5x4 0x6 97m) SR: 73.61

dismissalComment.html: superb catch by Dean Brownlie at deep square leg. He had to be mindful of the ropes just behind him, but he kept his balance and judged the catch to perfection. Coming back to the delivery, excellent short ball at 140 clicks, Head had to fetch this from outside off. The ball got big on him but he went through with the stroke and simply top-edged it to the fielder in the deep. Lot of credit to the bowler, for the effort.

dismissalText.commentary: James Faulkner c Taylor b Boult 0 (3b 0x4 0x6 3m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: there was a wide slip in place specifically for this. Faulkner is squared up by the late movement, gets a thick edge that was dying on Taylor, who moves low to his left to complete a stunning catch. This is outstanding tactics from New Zealand. First to place the fielder there, and then set the batsman up before eventually.  sending him on his way. The front foot is fine, the umpires were checking for the catch. Kumar Dharmasena, the third umpire, had a couple of replays, before relaying his decision to the on-field umpire.

dismissalText.commentary: Pat Cummins c Santner b Boult 27 (35b 1x4 2x6 57m) SR: 77.14

dismissalComment.html: one shot too many and he's gone! Cummins looks to go through with the pull but was beaten for pace and hurried into the stroke, ended up lobbing it to midwicket where Santner made no mistake. Relief in the New Zealand camp. Is that it for Australia?

dismissalText.commentary: Adam Zampa c Taylor b Boult 1 (5b 0x4 0x6 8m) SR: 20

dismissalComment.html: he's got five! Ross Taylor was brought in at wide first slip position precisely prior to this delivery and the plan comes off. This is a cutter, gets a bit of grip and bounce, Zampa hangs his bat out without any conviction, gets a thick edge and Taylor does the rest.

dismissalText.commentary: Josh Hazlewood b Boult 4 (5b 1x4 0x6 5m) SR: 80

dismissalComment.html: you beauty, Boult! Six wickets and New Zealand have regained the Chappell-Hadlee Trophy. Subtle change in pace with that length ball, Hazlewood look to force that through the off side, plays outside the line and can only get a thick inside edge back onto the stumps. New Zealand win the series 2-0. These are Boult's best figures in ODIs, his second five-wicket haul in his career, and both have come against Australia. The last time he did it - at the 2015 World Cup at Eden Park - was equally special.
